<TEXT>
tiny riverside fairy shrimps 
can keep splashing around in their swimming hole thanks to county 
supervisors who ordered developers to help save the recently 
discovered freshwater crustacean 
developers planned to bulldoze a lowlying pond and build more 
than 2500 homes unaware that the species whose ancestors date 
back millions of years occupied the seasonal pool 
riverside county supervisors on tuesday ordered the tolman co 
of irvine to preserve the threatened habitat after they were 
alerted by biologists who discovered the fairy shrimp species two 
years ago 
the 22legged fairy shrimp is about as wide as a pencil and 1 
inches long it has been described by biologists as the most 
primitive crustacean living in fresh water 
a group of biologists named the species the riverside fairy 
shrimp after finding them in 15acre skunk hollow pond and five 
smaller ponds in southern riverside county about 80 miles 
southeast of downtown los angeles 
the fairy shrimp population survives dry summer months by 
burying eggs in the clay soil of the seasonal pools the eggs of 
some desert species have been known to survive for as long as 25 
years between adequate rains 
the board of supervisors gave the developer and the biologists 
until sept 27 to come up with a proposal that would permit the 
survival of the fairy shrimp and tolmans proposed 2571unit 
housing project 
</TEXT>
