<TEXT>
the elderly manager of a 
hardware store in this farming village remembered brian mullin as 
a friendly lad a bricklayer who often dropped by for supplies 
he just got caught up in the troubles because he knew nothing 
else the manager said hes only one of hundreds of young men 
in the area who have been harassed every day by the security 
forces 
mullin 25 and two other local irish republican army men died 
in a british army ambush aug 30 as they drove along a country road 
near drumnakilly 5 miles north of here 
their funerals over the weekend drew mourners from all around 
the area and hundreds of riot police the mourners mostly 
catholic and the police mostly protestant faced each other in 
stony silence physically they were inches apart mentally a gulf 
separated them 
police said the three dead men were armed and dressed in ski 
masks when they died the london newspapers called them terrorists 
murderers and ira rats 
but in the countryside of county tyrone many residents knew 
these parttime guerrillas or their families and spoke of them in 
sympathetic terms 
their deaths helped exacerbate the divisions between local 
catholics and the iras most frequent targets in rural districts 
the police and the ulster defense regiment 
theres a majority of protestants with nothing wrong with 
them said a 28yearold decorator sitting on a grassy bank 
outside dunmoyle catholic church on saturday waiting for mullins 
hearse to pass 
its those that join the security forces we cant live with 
he said glancing at policemen searching mourners at a crossroads 
at the start of a twomile trek to mullins family farm outside 
sixmilecross 
like the store manager he spoke on condition of anonymity 
fearing retaliation for criticizing the police 
if you come up this road at 2 or 3 in the morning and youre 
stopped by them youre sure to get a kicking because of who you 
are he said the police force would be welcome surely if 
they were 5050 catholicprotestant and they were fair 
the police and army say they cant get catholic recruits because 
the ira would kill them as collaborators 
william gallagher 53 of strabane in neighboring county 
fermanagh said he was a political activist with two sons 
serving lengthy prison sentences for ira bombings 
the british never listen to anything except a gun he said 
you couldnt name three countries the british have not been at 
war with 
the mainly catholic ira is fighting to end british rule in 
predominantly protestant northern ireland and unite it with the 95 
percent catholic irish republic 
like many ira recruits in rural districts alongside the irish 
republics border the slain men led double lives their ira 
activities camouflaged by ordinary civilian pursuits 
brothers gerard and martin harte who were buried friday in 
their nearby home village of loughmacrory were leading players in 
the local gaelic football team 
gerard harte a 29yearold architect designed his own 
grandiose house overlooking the village his 21yearold brother 
was a carpenter both were married martin harte to mullins 
sister and each had an infant son 
police said gerard harte was the commander of the iras 
midtyrone unit and that his brother was responsible for selecting 
ira targets from police and ulster defense regiment ranks 
mullin whose elder brother patrick is serving a life sentence 
for the 1977 ira murder of a bus driver was questioned after a 
bomb killed eight british soldiers aug 20 in a bus in nearby 
ballygawley he was released without charge after five days 
news reports said the trio were on their way to kill an offduty 
member of the ulster defense regiment when soldiers ambushed their 
stolen car the government says the ira men fired first 
at mullins funeral riot squads massed to block any repetition 
of the ira gun salutes that have sparked clashes with police at 
previous burials 
the 2000 mourners inched along narrow country lanes flanked by 
long lines of police in helmets guns and riot shields they 
trudged through rainsodden fields climbing over ditches and 
hedges and scattering cows and sheep 
when one policeman fell over a barbedwire fence the crowd 
roared approval 
police ringed the church walls during the mass sometimes 
banging batons against shields in what sounded like a tribal beat 
three officers videotaped the crowd and a helicopter clattered 
overhead almost drowning out the graveside prayers 
when the service ended the crowd quickly dispersed the weather 
switched from driving rain to warm sunshine and the tensions from 
the 3hour service lifted 
