<TEXT>
windblown embers from a 
165000acre forest fire ignited rooftops wednesday inside the old 
faithful geyser complex of yellowstone national park after 
hundreds of tourists evacuated the area 
at least 17 buildings were destroyed as the big north fork fire 
moved into the outskirts of the complex wednesday afternoon when 
40mph winds shifted creating a wall of flame that forced 40 
firefighters to retreat from the lines 
when that firestorm went through there we had to move our 
people out of there said denny bungarz fire incident commander 
when you can feel the heat inside your car its time to move 
embers rained down on firefighters who wetted roofs inside the 
complex and activated a sprinkler atop the historic old faithful 
inn to protect the 84yearold log building a national historic 
landmark since 1987 
two cabins in the employee housing area were destroyed by the 
wall of flame and winds gusting to 50 mph showered sparks into the 
complex igniting the roofs of 14 other guest cabins and a utility 
shed bungarz said 
as winds died down late wednesday night authorities began to 
hope that the fire threat near the parks most popular attraction 
again was over i would consider it over bungarz said the 
main fire front passed through here it really fireproofed this 
area 
wednesdays evacuation of the geyser complex was the first in 
the 116year history of the oldest us national park ordered as 
the fire burned to within a halfmile of the parks most popular 
attraction 
about 800 visitors calmly left the 320room inn which park 
officials decided to close for the season more than a month early 
later however park officials decided to allow day visitors in the 
area 
inside the complex firefighters hosed down buildings to protect 
them from flames as a handful of tourists sightseeing when the 
flames erupted were held in the area until fire activity slowed 
its the safest place to be in spite of what it feels like 
bungarz said 
