<TEXT>
michael milken who was charged by 
a federal lawsuit with insider trading almost singlehandedly 
built junkbond financing into the tool of choice for corporate 
raiders during the past dozen years 
milken was seen for years as a wall street whiz kid who had 
helped transform drexel burnham lambert inc from a minor player 
into a powerhouse 
even when it became known several months ago that he was under 
investigation for insider trading milken and drexel took the 
offensive 
drexel waged a publicrelations blitz stressing the role of 
junk bonds notes that are highly risky but offer high yields in 
helping small companies get off the ground and downplaying their 
role megabuck takeover battles 
the normally secretive milken 42 began accepting speaking 
engagements and granting some interviews with the condition that 
questions about the securities and exchange commission and the 
investigation of him were off limits 
his comments focused almost solely on his latest pet plan to 
alleviate the latin american debt crisis by swapping debt for 
equity or selling securities backed by those countries oil and 
silver resources 
milken reportedly makes 40 million a year as the head of 
drexels junkbond operation that is several times more than the 
firms chairman milkens personal fortune has been estimated at 
more than 500 million 
he lives with his children and wife lori his high school 
sweetheart whom he married at age 22 in a house on the former 
estate of the late actor clark gable in suburban encino an 
uppermiddleclass section of the san fernando valley two miles 
from his childhood home 
milkens fascination with finance dates to his boyhood at age 
10 a favorite pastime was poring over tax returns prepared by his 
father an accountant 
after studying business at the university of california 
berkeley and the university of pennsylvanias wharton school 
milken went to work for drexel firestone amp co in philadelphia as a 
junior bond trader 
drexel merged with burnham amp co in 1973 and lambert brussels 
witter in 1976 and milkens job was moved to new york milken 
worked hard to make a name for himself but never became acclimated 
to the east 
in 1977 he persuaded drexel to let him move the companys 
junkbond operations from wall street to beverly hills just off 
swank rodeo drive 
milken became enormously successful in california building a 
closeknit network of junkbond investors he is in charge of the 
150 people who work at drexels junkbond operation 
he still works 12 to 13 hours a day seven days a week and wont 
tolerate lack of drive among those who work for him 
