<TEXT>
at the advice of the nations 
bishops pope john paul ii will bypass south africa the most 
populous and dominant country in southern africa when he begins a 
visit to the region saturday 
south african catholics have written to newspapers and their 
church expressing anger and disappointment that the pope is not 
stopping in their land he will visit zimbabwe lesotho 
mozambique botswana and swaziland all of which border south 
africa 
some south africa catholics said they would withhold donations 
that would be used to finance the popes visit to the poorer 
neighboring countries others suggested the pope could have done 
some good by bringing a message of peace reconciliation and 
respect for human rights to racially divided south africa 
the dispute is part of a growing tension between the south 
african government and church leaders who actively oppose 
apartheid under which the nations black majority has no voice in 
national affairs 
no one in the church has said that the itinerary for the sept 
1019 visit is a snub of the south african government or a 
demonstration of the vaticans disapproval of apartheid 
but the zimbabwe government said john paul was protesting 
apartheid by not going to south africa it banned south 
africanbased foreign journalists from covering the pope in 
zimbabwe 
foreign minister pik bothas office issued a statement aug 4 
saying the bishops were to blame for the pope skipping south africa 
because they had not invited him although they had been told the 
government would welcome a visit 
the southern african catholic bishops conference said it invited 
the pope to come to south africa in 1982 but has been unable to 
arrange a date the conference said it would be impractical to 
squeeze a large country like south africa into a tour already 
covering five nations 
there has been a lot of misunderstanding about the whole 
thing said the archbishop of cape town stephen naidoo the 
pope never said he wouldnt come 
he called bothas aug 4 statement mischievous 
the pope said in july that he would like to visit south africa 
some day but that the bishops told him it would not be appropriate 
at this time he did not elaborate 
south african security police this week went to the home of 
anglican archbishop desmond tutu in cape town to collect a 
recording of his latest sermon they were investigating whether he 
had violated emergency regulations by calling for a boycott of 
october municipal elections 
law and order minister adriaan vlok said last week the 
government may clip the wings of activist clergymen who vowed 
to begin a civil disobedience campaign against emergency rules 
the rev smangaliso mkhatshwa secretarygeneral of the catholic 
bishops conference was released from detention last year after 
church officials filed court affidavits in which he swore he was 
being tortured he was subsequently charged with possession of a 
gun which he denies 
the schedule for the popes 10day visit includes beatification 
of a french missionary in lesotho a bishops conference in 
zimbabwe and outdoor masses in botswana swaziland and mozambique 
the pope received south african president pw botha at the 
vatican in 1984 and there are plans for him to send greetings 
during one of his two flights over the country on his way to 
lesotho and to swaziland 
lesotho is surrounded by south africa and swaziland is bordered 
on three sides by its huge neighbor hundreds of thousands of south 
africans black and white are expected to cross the border to see 
the pope many thousands are also expected in botswana and zimbabwe 
just as south africa dominates communications trade 
transportation and politics in the region its influence will be 
felt strongly during the popes trip 
south african firms are supplying transportation food water 
and health services broadcasting and emergency equipment to be 
used on many of the popes stops 
local coordinating committees are selling papal souvenirs 
through south african franchises to defray the expenses of 
building podiums for the outdoor rallies providing accommodations 
for dignitaries and pilgrims and arranging for security and 
traffic control 
 
