<TEXT>
a vaccine is highly effective against an epidemic 
form of encephalitis that is a major health problem among children 
in parts of asia according to a report published today 
the us army study tested a vaccine used to control the 
japanese encephalitis virus although its primary victims are 
schoolage children the virus also affects travelers and military 
personnel 
encephalitis vaccine has been administered to millions of 
children in japan since the 1960s but the army study was the first 
to test the effectiveness of the most widely used versions of the 
vaccine 
at 230 per dose the vaccine is relatively expensive and 
japanese encephalitis is still a major health hazard in many parts 
of asia 
the study was conducted on 65224 children in northern thailand 
where the disease strikes 10 to 20 of every 100000 people this 
rate is similar to polio at its worst in the united states 
according to a report in the new england journal of medicine 
twothirds of youngsters received two doses of vaccine while the 
rest got dummy shots the attack rate was 5 per 100000 in those 
getting vaccine and 51 per 100000 in the comparison group 
the study directed by dr charles h hoke of the walter reed 
army institute of research in washington concludes that the vaccine 
is safe and effective 
in an accompanying editorial dr thomas p monath of the us 
centers for disease control in atlanta noted that the vaccine is 
not available to americans abroad because of its manufacturers 
concerns about liability 
however he said efforts are under way to resolve this issue 
and the us food and drug administration is reviewing applications 
to sell the vaccine in this country 
