<TEXT>
babies who are vaccinated against whooping cough 
face no unusual risk of crib death as some experts had feared 
according to a major study published today 
the report was based on a review of 129834 vaccinated babies 
it found that the risk of crib death is actually lower than usual 
after the shots 
some research has suggested that babies have an increased risk 
of sudden infant death syndrome or sids immediately after 
receiving immunization for whopping cough also known as pertussis 
babies are routinely given the socalled dtp vaccine which 
protects them from diphtheria tetanus and pertussis 
the study by dr marie r griffin vanderbilt university school 
of medicine finds no support for this concern 
we conclude in this large population of children there was no 
increase in the risk of sids after immunization with the dtp 
vaccine they wrote in the new england journal of medicine 
doctors generally recommend that children receive five doses of 
the vaccine three during the first six months one after the 
first birthday and one before starting school 
crib death is considered to be the sudden unexpected death of 
an infant or young child when no specific cause of death can be 
found it is most common before the first birthday accounting for 
30 percent of all deaths in the age group 
the study was based on children born between 1974 and 1984 in 
four tennessee counties the researchers compared the risk of sids 
deaths during the first month after vaccination with the risk later 
in infancy 
they found that that during the first week after vaccination 
the risk was less than 20 percent that of later periods 
the most plausible explanation for the decreased rate of sids 
in the period immediately after immunization is that children may 
be immunized when they are in better health and that this healthier 
state is associated with a lower risk of sids they wrote 
</TEXT>
