<TEXT>
harold rosson a pioneering cinematographer 
whose work included the wizard of oz and who was married to 
screen legend jean harlow has died at age 93 
rosson died tuesday at his home in palm beach fla said robert 
terry a nephew 
his first movie was the silent david harum in 1915 he went 
on to direct the photography for such movies as gentlemen prefer 
blondes in 1928 treasure island in 1934 duel in the sun 
in 1947 and singin in the rain in 1952 his last film was el 
dorado in 1967 
during his 52year career many of hollywoods top directors 
including cecil b demille allan dwan howard hawks josef von 
sternberg and king vidor requested him for their films 
he helped bring the elegant polish to metro goldwyn mayer films 
of the 1930s and 1940s including the wizard of oz in 1939 
rosson a native of new york city became ms harlows third and 
last husband in 1933 after her death in 1937 he married yvonne 
crellin they later divorced he had no children 
he shared an honorary academy award in 1936 with w howard 
greene for pioneering color cinematography on the desert melodrama 
the garden of allah rosson said it was the first color 
photography he attempted 
he was also nominated for oscars for boom town in 1940 
thirty seconds over tokyo in 1944 the asphalt jungle in 
1950 and the bad seed in 1956 
funeral services were scheduled for saturday in hollywood 
</TEXT>
