<TEXT>
aspiring principals for the first time will 
not be required to have teaching experience under a new state 
policy 
educators said the policy makes new jersey the first state to 
open the principals office to nonteachers 
the plan approved wednesday by new jerseys board of education 
increases standards for all candidates but drops a requirement of 
three years teaching experience 
the plan will allow the new principals to get teaching 
experience as they go 
these new standards create a rigorous procedure for preparing 
all future principals and at the same time open up the system so 
that local districts can select the best potential candidates 
regardless of background education commissioner saul cooperman 
said in a statement after the board meeting in jamesburg 
principals without education backgrounds will be designated as 
being part of a pilot project it is to be reviewed by an 
independent panel in four years education department spokesman 
roger shatzkin said 
during that period the state will allow the hiring of no more 
than 50 new principals who lack teaching background he said the 
applicants will be required to have a masters degree in 
management however 
principals with less than a year of teaching experience will 
have to teach one class period a day for at least a year and 
candidates with less than a yer of teaching experience will have to 
teach for two years 
in addition they will be required to complete 135 hours of 
graduate study in education during their one to twoyear residency 
cooperman said the changes will give new jersey schools a wider 
and better field from which to choose principals 
chris pipho a spokesman in denver for the education commission 
of the states which follows school policies across the country 
said he knows of no other state that allows nonteachers to be 
principals 
