<TEXT>
centuries of hate and discrimination between 
perus rich and poor have spawned a vicious leftist insurgency that 
could lead to civil war the head of a blueribbon senate panel on 
violence warned thursday 
either we make a concerted effort at a national plan for 
pacification or face the possibility of a country caught in a 
civil war sen enrique bernales said in making public the 
commissions report 
poverty racism and government corruption are other major causes 
of the eightyear insurrection of the maoist shining path guerrilla 
group said the study conducted by a panel of 11 senators 
political violence in peru is not the result of poverty alone 
but of humiliation oppression hate between classes racism 
bernales said 
bernales said the 389page report which probes the roots of 
violence and offers possible solutions is the most extensive of 
its kind ever undertaken in peru 
the commission said the white ruling class has maintained the 
subjugation of indian peasants in the andean highlands first begun 
by spanish conquerors and continued by the aristocracy 
it said the peasants who make up about 40 percent of perus 
population are the most uneducated impoverished and ignored 
sector of society and are frequent objects of scorn 
this has become an intolerable humiliation they are being 
pushed to the border and are questioning the existing order 
violence has resulted the report said 
the commission which used government and private studies in its 
findings said 11605 people have been killed and property damage 
has reached 10 billion in the maoist revolt 
the panel said that the economy also has deteriorated 
dramatically 
the country is in the same situation as it was 15 years ago 
it has lost all movement toward developing said bernales 
mounting problems have sparked an exodus of skilled workers and 
professionals the report said 125000 peruvians emigrated in the 
past four years about half to the united states 
in a nationwide survey which sampled residents of the 
terrorridden mountain states of ayacucho and huancavelica for the 
first time ever the commission found 60 percent of perus 20 
million people believe the government has been ineffective in 
dealing with terrorism 
the commission said the insurgency repressive countermeasures 
by government forces and drug trafficking have sparked political 
instability and undermined participation in perus democracy 
about 300000 peruvian families are linked to narcotics 
trafficking according to the study the peasants grow coca the 
raw material of cocaine on small jungle plots for their livelihood 
the shining path recently opened a new front in the cocagrowing 
zone the commission urged greater efforts be made toward feasible 
crop substitution programs 
it also urged government forces to reject illegal tactics in 
dealing with guerrillas 
the state and society must stay within the law in defending 
itself said bernales 
the states of emergency to counter rebels now in effect in 
seven states where more than 40 percent of the population lives 
should be phased out to strengthen respect for democracy the 
commission said 
the panel recommended a national consensus be reached quickly on 
how to resist the guerrillas and it urged radical changes in 
perus rigid class structure 
the commission also proposed that police and the military 
undergo training in respecting human rights 
</TEXT>
