<TEXT>
a federal judge was confronted thursday with 
conflicting arguments over whether to let detroits two daily 
newspapers complete a partial merger approved last month by 
thenattorney general edwin meese iii 
william schultz attorney for a michigan group of readers and 
advertisers opposed to the arrangement accused owners of the 
detroit free press and the detroit news of cutting prices to put 
each other out of business or eventually qualify for a lucrative 
joint operating agreement under the newspaper preservation act 
but a justice department attorney thomas millet said there was 
absolutely no evidence that the two newspapers had colluded 
the arrangement approved by meese before he left office would 
allow the morning free press owned by knightridder inc to 
merge its commercial and business operations with the news bought 
in 1986 by gannett co 
knightridder has threatened to close the free press which has 
sustained 100 million in losses in nine years if the partial 
merger is not allowed to proceed 
the deal was temporarily blocked by court order last month to 
give us district judge george revercomb a chance to consider the 
legal challenge by michigan citizens for a free press 
revercomb said he would rule next week on the groups request 
for an injunction barring the merger 
the michigan group of readers and advertisers charges that the 
two newspapers set out to try to put each other out of business by 
cutting advertising and circulation rates or to qualify for a joint 
operating agreement 
knightridders strategy was to sustain shortterm losses with 
its eye on very longterm profits under a joint operating 
agreement allowed by the laws antitrust exemption schultz said 
schultz argued that meeses decision to allow the partial merger 
was arbitrary because he ignored the administrative law judges 
conclusion that if the merger were not approved the news which 
has also posted significant losses would eventually raise its 
prices thereby allowing the free press to do the same 
millet said there was absolutely no evidence of collusion 
between the free press and the news which was not acquired by 
gannett until several months before the merger application was made 
in 1986 
the fact that these two papers considered the option and 
discused this over a period of time is not an argument that a joa 
shouldnt occur millet said 
such discussions were a natural consequence of the losses 
the two papers continued to suffer while waging the cutthroat 
newspaper war he said 
clark clifford an attorney representing knightridder said the 
news rejected several overtures from the free press about forming a 
joint operating agreement 
the news answer was always there is the door goodbye 
said clifford an elder statesmen of the democratic party and a 
knightridder director 
while the free press was locked in bitter competition with the 
news every year except one they lost more money than they lost 
the year before clifford said 
clifford said 2200 jobs would be lost if the free press closed 
its doors compared to 600 to 800 lost positions under the proposed 
merger 
