<TEXT>
south korea has made significant improvements in 
human rights as it prepares to host the olympics but the 
government still holds 600 political prisoners and tortures some of 
them amnesty international said thursday 
the human rights group said in a report that some political 
prisoners were jailed after unfair trials but that torture has 
decreased 
government sensitivity to world attention during the sept 17 to 
oct 2 olympics may help improve the situation but the games do 
not guarantee changes a representative of the londonbased group 
said 
the limits of freedom of expression have expanded the 
atmosphere is remarkably more free than before amnesty 
international researcher francoise vandale said at a briefing on 
the report entitled detention of prisoners of conscience and 
torture continue 
the report said south korea should release more political 
prisoners end torture and illtreatment of detainees and change 
laws to allow peaceful expression of opposition to the government 
major political changes since last summer have ushered in some 
improvements in human rights the report noted 
the government of president roh taewoo came to power after roh 
then chairman of the governing party pledged democratic reforms 
including release of political prisoners in response to violent 
demonstrations in june 1987 
national assembly elections last april gave the opposition a 
majority a startling change for a country long ruled by a party 
with almost complete power 
the assembly is debating several changes in laws on national 
security and demonstrations and amnesty international called for 
amendments to exclude from their scope peaceful acts of 
opposition to the government 
the changes have given political prisoners limited hope there 
have been releases and amnesties but we think theyve been too 
few ms vandale said 
the government says nearly 1300 political prisoners have been 
released since last year but amnesty international says the number 
is only 400 
the organization also said 4000 former political prisoners 
civil rights have been restored in this period about half the 
number claimed by the government 
arrests on political grounds have continued with about 600 
people imprisoned for political or trade union activities the 
report said 
of these about onethird have been convicted as far back as 
1958 for antistate activities such as espionage and given 
sentences from five years to life 
another onethird were arrested during nationwide strikes in 
1987 and the rest are thought to be students arrested in the past 
year during antigovernment demonstrations 
among the 600 amnesty international is calling for the release 
of 28 it has adopted as prisoners of conscience and it is 
investigating the cases of another 70 
amnesty international defines prisoners of conscience as those 
detained for belief color sex ethnic origin language or 
religion provided they havent used or advocated violence 
students who threw rocks in demonstrations could not be considered 
an official said 
constitutional amendments have strenthened laws protecting 
prisoners rights but in practice these rights are still not 
always respected amnesty international said 
it said relatives and lawyers have been denied access to any 
information about detainees and prisoners have been isolated 
beaten and deprived of sleep in the first days after their arrest 
the group has not heard of water torture cases since several 
instances in the last two years in which police were arrested for 
torture or abuse of a detainee 
asked if amnesty international felt the government was making 
changes with the olympics in mind the researcher said i suppose 
the government is sensitive to its political image but i believe 
the release of political prisoners has more to do with the balance 
of political parties 
she said that in the long term of course the attention of the 
whole world matters but things have changed very quickly in 
korea we just dont know what might happen after the games 
</TEXT>
