schools and libraries face growing pressure to 
censor the books children read according to a report released 
thursday by the american association of school administrators 
pressures that could result in censorship are increasing and 
that has an adverse effect on the ability of the schools to provide 
a broadbased education for children who will be our future 
leaders said judith krug director of the associations office 
for intellectual freedom 
this pressure comes from people who want to impose their views 
on the educational system by removing or restricting use of certain 
materials according to the report censorship and selection 
issues and answers for schools 
the study was published jointly by the administrators group and 
the american library association 
over the past five years the number of challenges to library 
books and school materials increased by 168 percent the groups 
said 
in many cases the study says those seeking to censor materials 
see themselves as living in a hostile world surrounded by enemies 
people whose world is filled with oughts and shoulds and 
any indication that other people are freer in their decisionmaking 
processes arouses in them severe feelings of anxiety and 
resentment 
it is essential that schools reach out to these people before 
controversy can arise the report suggests cited as a possible 
solution was one case where parents who had heard reports of 
questionable material in some school books were invited to the 
school to read and discuss the books in question 
the teachers learned things from the parents while the parents 
got to understand the books and came to trust the teachers the 
report said 
