<TEXT>
a memorial service will mark the 25th 
anniversary of a church bombing that killed four black girls and 
focused national attention on the struggle for civil rights in 
alabamas largest city 
in embracing our history there is healing join us reads an 
invitation from the committee for sept 15 a group of black 
and white birmingham residents planning the ceremony 
four girls ages 11 14 and 16 were killed in the 1963 
dynamite blast at the 16th street baptist church the girls were 
changing into choir robes in the basement on a sunday morning when 
the blast tore through the room twentythree others were injured 
the bombing one of dozens of racially motivated bombings in 
birmingham in the late 1950s and early 1960s remained unsolved 
until 1977 when robert edward chambliss a white retired auto 
mechanic was convicted of murder and sentenced to life in prison 
chambliss died in prison in 1985 
committee members said the remembrance will give blacks and 
whites a chance to remember not just the bombing but the civil 
rights struggle 
we as a city are merely looking at ourselves and saying that 
we remember said committee member bette lee 
the sept 15 event will feature a number of speakers including 
the rev john cross pastor of the church in 1963 and now an 
official with the southern baptist convention it will be held at 
kelly ingram park a site adjacent to the church where a civil 
rights museum is planned 
</TEXT>
