<TEXT>
burundi shaken by a wave of ethnic killings 
last month has assured the world bank that all its citizens share 
equally in the benefits of the banks multimilliondollar aid 
programs for the central african country a world bank official 
said thursday 
we were terribly shocked and dismayed by the tragic events in 
burundi edward vk jaycox world bank vice president for 
africa told reporters at least 5000 people were reported slain 
in battles during august between burundis ruling tutsi tribe and 
the majority hutus 
bank officials were especially distressed by the violence 
because the government that took power in a 1987 coup had pushed 
forward vigorously a policy of equality jaycox said the hutus 
make up 85 percent of the 5 million population but hold relatively 
few government or military posts 
the reforms included elimination of burundis internal pass 
laws which were oppressive to the majority hutus and 
restricted the labor market jaycox continued 
burundi authorities have assured the world bank that peace and 
inclusion of all burundians in the development process is the 
policy of the government he said 
the world bank constantly evaluates its policies in all 
countries but there is little it can do to mitigate ethnic violence 
beyond seeing that our programs are supportive of progress for 
all said jaycox an american 
the world bank lent burundi 1535 million dollars during fiscal 
1988 for projects promoting agriculture rural development health 
nutrition education small business and birth control 
