mumps the oncecommon childhood disease is 
declining again after two years on the rise federal health 
officials reported thursday 
the centers for disease control reported that mumps was down by 
twothirds through the first 30 weeks of this year with 3166 
cases reported in that time 
the cdc also reported details of a mumps outbreak last year in 
three chicago financial markets which illustrated the potential 
seriousness of the usually mild disease the costs from the 116 
cases averaged nearly 1500 per patient 
mumps reached a record low in the united states in 1985 when 
2982 cases were reported down 98 percent from the 152000 
reported in 1968 the first year for the licensed mumps vaccine 
mumps reporting then rose over the next two years to 7790 cases 
in 1986 and 12299 in preliminary reports from 1987 
the cases reported in the first 30 weeks of 1988 mark a 67 
percent drop from the same period in 1987 the cdc said 
the report made no speculation on this years decrease 
recent outbreaks have occurred in high schools and on college 
campuses the cdc noted that those outbreaks would include some 
people who may not have been vaccinated because they were children 
between 1967 when the vaccine was first licensed and 1977 when 
it was added to the list of vaccines recommended for all children 
over 1 year 
one major outbreak last year occurred among an older group 
employees at three futures exchanges in chicago between aug 18 
and dec 25 76 cases occurred at one exchange 39 cases occurred 
at a second exchange and one more case occurred at a third exchange 
the patients at the three exchanges which were not identified 
could not be positively linked the atlantabased agency said 
but researchers believe there may have been contacts between the 
three locations which could not be documented said dr karen 
kaplan a cdc epidemiologist 
the cdc was able to get vaccination information for 82 patients 
more than onethird believed they had been immunized against mumps 
but only three could prove it with records 
the vaccine is how this could have been averted ms kaplan 
said we suggest that adults have a complete immunization record 
with all recommended shots but nobody thinks about adult 
immunization 
the costs associated with the 116patient outbreak including 
doctors visits hospitalization for nine patients medications and 
missed work came to 120738 or 1473 a case the cdc said 
that the cdc said contrasted dramatically with the cost of 
mumps vaccine less than 5 a dose at public clinics about 9 
at a doctors office 
mumps which causes painful swelling in the neck is usually 
mild but can cause serious problems in other parts of the body 
particularly in adolescents and young adults serious complications 
can include deafness orchitis in the testicles and meningitis or 
encephalitis in the nervous system 
