<TEXT>
the countrys two largest purchasers of home 
mortgages announced thursday that they have reached agreement on 
ways to streamline and simplify the often timeconsuming process of 
obtaining a home mortgage 
the agreement was reached between the federal home loan mortgage 
corp known as freddie mac and the federal national mortgage 
association known as fannie mae both corporations buy mortgages 
from primary lenders and resell them as mortgagebacked securities 
thus increasing the pool of money available to make home loans 
the two companies along with the federal housing administration 
the veterans administration and the government national mortage 
association have been participating for the past year in a task 
force seeking to standardize and simplify the mortgage application 
process 
john teutsch president of the mortgage bankers association an 
organization of local lenders said the agreement between freddie 
mac and fannie mae was an important first step and should set the 
stage for more progress in the future 
the mortgage group estimated that further progress could 
eventually cut in half the time it takes to get a mortgage 
approved at present this waiting period ranges from 45 to 60 days 
during the past 50 years the mortgage origination process had 
become unnecessarily complicated for both consumers and lenders 
alike it was time to turn back the tide of paperwork teutsch 
said 
teutsch said at a news conference that fannie mae and freddie 
mac had both agreed to revise their mortgage eligibility 
requirements and underwriting guidelines to make them more uniform 
this is critical because local lenders follow these guidelines 
closely in making home loans since loans that do not conform are 
not eligible to be purchased by the agencies for resale to 
investors about twothirds of all residential mortgages end up 
being resold into the secondary market 
david james croft freddie macs executive vice president for 
operations said that the task force had been useful in resolving 
several differences in underwriting guidelines between the two 
corporations 
with freddie mac and fannie mae having the same basic 
policies lenders will not have to separate loans during 
origination based on which agency they plan to sell the mortgages 
to that will streamline operations for mortgage lenders resulting 
in better rates for borrowers croft said 
under the guidelines the two agencies reached agreement on 20 
different underwriting differences including loantovalue ratios 
multiple mortgages to the same borrower seller contributions age 
of credit documents and how to classify investment properties 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

