<TEXT>
a vaccine for dangerous childhood diseases that 
include a form of meningitis has had mixed results according to 
three studies in a prominent medical journal 
but an accompanying editorial in fridays journal of the 
american medical association says the results should not stop 
doctors from giving patients a new version of the vaccine 
like it or not we must often make decisions in the absence of 
incontrovertible evidence dr edward a mortimer jr of case 
western reserve university school of medicine in cleveland wrote 
in the editorial 
the original vaccine for fighting a bacterium called 
haemophilus influenzae type b was first licensed for use in the 
united states in april 1985 largely because a clinical trial in 
finland had found it was 90 percent effective in preventing disease 
in children 18 to 71 months old and older 
an updated version of the vaccine approved in december by the 
food and drug administration is designed to improve protection for 
younger children 
a committee of the centers for disease control has recommended 
its use for all children at 18 months officials said 
the studies published in fridays journal reviewed use of the 
original vaccine which could be considered obsolete except for its 
cheaper cost said dr eugene shapiro of the yale university school 
of medicine leader of one of the studies 
shapiro said the first vaccine hasnt been shown to cause harm 
so could still be used 
the bacterium infects about 20000 us children each year and 
in about 12000 of those cases takes the form of bacterial 
meningitis which can cause retardation said dr lee h harrison 
who led one of the cdc studies 
among other problems caused by the bacterium are infections of 
the blood or of the epiglottis which can cause suffocation he 
said 
the bacterium is believed to be transmitted by persontoperson 
contact officials said 
about 5 percent of cases of disease caused by the bacterium are 
fatal said harrison 
he said he knew of no states which require the vaccine but that 
it is administered to about 30 percent of the nations children 
when the original vaccine was approved for use in the united 
states information on its effectiveness was limited doubts were 
raised by some doctors who questioned its ability to provide 
protection 
according to separate reports in the chicagobased medical 
journal a study in all or part of six states found a 45 percent 
effective rate of protection from immunization in 18 to 
59montholds and another conducted in parts of three states 
found it 88 percent effective in 2 to 6yearolds 
a third study of children beginning at age 2 in minnesota 
found that the vaccine may even increase risk of the disease by 55 
percent 
but authors of the minnesota study noted they dealt with just 88 
cases and that chance alone could explain the instances of 
bacteriumrelated disease 
i have trouble puting a lot of weight on the minnesota 
study said harrison 
mortimer said the newer vaccine has been shown to create more 
antibodies in younger children so the probable benefits outweigh 
the costs and risks if any and i recommend use of this new 
vaccine for children beginning at 18 months of age pending further 
information 
</TEXT>
