representatives from the post office and the 
communication workers union met thursday in an attempt to end 
britains weekold mail strike 
international mail service remained at a standstill but about 
half of britains 1500 local post offices opened with nonstriking 
and temporary staff who made sporadic deliveries said post office 
spokeswoman caroline francke 
the walkout began aug 31 as a 24hour strike called in a 
dispute over bonuses paid to new recruits in london and southeast 
england where the cost of living is high and the post office has 
trouble attracting workers because of low unemployment 
the strike now has no time limit with the union demanding that 
the bonuses be paid nationally or not at all 
until there is a concrete framework agreed on over the central 
recruitment issue and a formula over getting postmen back to work 
quickly these exploratory talks will go on said ms francke 
union president alan tuffin said thursday we are no nearer 
reaching an agreement 
a spokesman would not confirm whether tuffin joined the talks 
about 100000 of the unions 140000 members stayed off the job 
thursday said ms francke and only one of britains 82 main 
postal sorting centers in belfast northern ireland opened for 
business 
more than 100 million pieces of mail have piled up since the 
strike began said ms francke mail boxes around the country have 
been sealed 
liverpool police said strikers in that city 200 miles northwest 
of london behaved peacefully thursday but picket line violence 
during the week led to the arrest of five strikers for disorderly 
conduct 
the strike has disrupted business and the work of government 
agencies 
a watchdog body the mail users association said wednesday the 
dispute is costing british industry 43 million a day 
