<TEXT>
five policemen and a girl were 
slightly hurt when a bomb planted in a van parked outside a village 
police station exploded thursday police said 
the explosion which caused extensive damage to the police 
station building and nearby houses happened at the county tyrone 
village of coagh 25 miles west of belfast 
a press officer at belfast police headquarters who in 
accordance with british practice declined to be identified said a 
warning was telephoned to police at coagh shortly before the blast 
police were evacuating people from nearby houses when the bomb 
went off police said the girl was believed to have been in a 
telephone booth near the police station at the time of the 
explosion they did not have her age but said she was in her early 
teens 
one of the five injured policemen and the girl were taken to a 
hospital at nearby magherafelt the other four injured policemen 
did not require hospital treatment 
no group immediately claimed responsibility for the blast but 
suspicion inevitably fell on the irish republican army 
the mainly roman catholic ira is fighting to end british rule in 
northern ireland it wants to unite the predominantly protestant 
province with the 95percent catholic republic of ireland under 
socialist rule 
</TEXT>
