<TEXT>
tropical storm florence moved north in the southern 
gulf of mexico on thursday and forecasters said highlevel winds 
were preventing it from strengthening as much as expected 
at 1030 pm edt the national hurricane center reported 
florence had 55 mph winds and was drifting north at 5 mph about 
375 miles south of new orleans the storm center was near latitude 
245 north and longitude 892 west 
forecaster jim gross said air currents high above florence were 
blowing the top off its thunderstorms keeping winds from 
intensifying to the 74 mph level that would classify the system as 
a hurricane 
right now its maintaining the status quo gross said he 
added that because of weak steering currents it was impossible to 
predict where the storm was headed 
were still looking at a threat but we dont know what 
direction it is going to take gross said 
he said it was not unusual for a storm to stall in the gulf for 
several days before moving toward land 
the louisiana office of state parks said thursday that grand 
isle state park would be closed friday because of high tides caused 
by the approaching tropical storm 
spokeswoman debbie woodiel said she did not know how long the 
park which is on the gulf of mexico would be closed 
florence is the sixth named storm of the 1988 atlantic hurricane 
season only debby which also formed in the gulf reached minimal 
hurricane status briefly 
the 12th and 13th tropical depressions of the season formed in 
the atlantic late thursday afternoon 
the 12th was centered about 300 miles eastsoutheast of barbados 
with top winds of about 30 mph the depression was drifting 
westward at 1015 mph and was expected to continue this motion for 
the next 24 hours 
the 13th depression was located about 400 miles northeast of the 
cape verde islands off the west coast of africa moving north at 
2025 mph with winds of 35 mph the system was not expected to 
intensify forecasters said 
