<TEXT>
ara dinkjian leader of the group night ark 
talks about his music by first explaining what its not pop jazz 
folk or classical 
yet the lyrical and often haunting compositions of the band meld 
them all into a curiously attractive eclectic fusion of eastern 
and western styles 
you hear a very strong middle eastern armenian flavor with 
all of the other elements creeping in and out of the music of 
night ark says dinkjian 
most americans have a further history in europe or in asia 
thats a part of them what im doing is opening my eyes and my 
heart to everything that i am and have been he said 
dinkjian who lives in nutley nj has a diverse musical 
background at age 5 he performed at the new york worlds fair as 
part of an armenian ensemble and grew up listening to the beatles 
and jazz he studied western classical music in college 
in night ark dinkjian plays a variety of exotic middle eastern 
stringed instruments oud cumbus canoon saz and writes and 
arranges most of the fourpiece bands music 
keyboardist armen donelian and percussionist arto tuncboyaci 
share dinkjians armenian heritage while bassist ed schuller finds 
in night ark an opportunity to explore new sounds and technique 
while the band members decline to call their music jazz they 
perform mostly in jazz clubs and night arks two albums on the rca 
novus label are targeted primarily at jazz audiences those 
audiences dinkjian says are generally receptive to night arks 
often unconventional rhythms and melodies 
at its best night ark plays a distinctive and frequently 
compelling music reminiscent of the turkishinspired jazz played a 
number of years ago by flutist herbie mann 
but at its worst the band drifts into lazy renditions of 
timeworn pop standards producing a music that ends up sounding 
like some uninspired new age elevator music 
the major disappointment is in the squandering of talent and 
ideas on a lame version of carole kings youve got a friend 
says william kinnally reviewing night arks second album 
moments in jazziz magazine 
but performing recently at the jazz club fat tuesdays night 
ark relied on its original compositions to charm receptive 
listeners 
night ark the name is a reference to biblical noahs ark 
which legend has it came to rest on armenias mount ararat 
retains several middle eastern musical fundamentals to produce its 
sound 
between two adjacent notes on a piano theres an infinite 
amount of notes that are inaccessible to western instruments but 
can be played by eastern musicians dinkjian said 
sometimes when people hear an arabic song it sounds out of 
tune he said the reason why my music doesnt sound strange is 
that i have slipped in all of those funny notes but carefully added 
the harmony behind it weve kind of buffered it 
night ark also employs rhythms unusual in western music 
this is not a jazz fusion gimmick this is the beat i was 
brought up with dinkjian said 
the insistent percussion is not alienating the western 
audience but tries to bring them in and say welcome youre going 
to like this 
