<TEXT>
a key figure in what federal prosecutors call 
wall streets secondbiggest insider trading scandal ever has 
pleaded guilty to criminal charges amid indications that others may 
be charged 
stephen suikuan wang jr a 24yearold former junior analyst 
with the venerable firm morgan stanley amp co pleaded guilty 
wednesday in us district court in manhattan to the first criminal 
charges leveled in the case 
wang who was free on a 250000 personal recognizance bond 
also agreed to plead guilty to a criminal charge in connection with 
a separate previously undisclosed insider trading scheme he 
allegedly undertook when he first began working for morgan stanley 
in june 1986 
us attorney rudolph w giuliani who outlined the charges at a 
news conference said wang was cooperating with the government and 
that the investigation was continuing an indication that others 
may be charged 
us district judge kevin duffy set sentencing for oct 19 wang 
faces a maximum punishment of 15 years in prison and 750000 in 
fines for the three fraud counts against him 
the charges were the first criminal counts made in the scandal 
first dicslosed in late june in a civil complaint by the securities 
and exchange commission 
prosecutors charged wang with using his position at morgan 
stanley to steal marketsensitive information about pending 
takeovers and other confidential matters in which the firm played a 
role 
the government alleged wang peddled the information starting in 
june 1987 to a taiwanese businessman fred c lee who allegedly 
used it to make at least 19 million in profitable stock trades in 
more than 14 companies and shared about 200000 with wang 
lee was named as an unindicted coconspirator but giuliani 
declined to explain why lee was not charged federal officials said 
lee also known by his chinese name chwan hong lee was in taiwan 
the sec has frozen the usbased assets of both men and 
requested return of the 19 million plus triple penalties for a 
total of 76 million 
that amount makes the case the secondbiggest insider trading 
scheme next to the record 100 million in illicit profits and 
penalties surrendered by nowimprisoned wall street speculator ivan 
boesky nearly two years ago 
the wang case is considered significant not only because of the 
amount of money involved but because the alleged abuses came at 
the height of a public uproar over wall street greed and corruption 
highlighted by the boesky scandal it suggested that insider 
trading remains a deeprooted problem 
giuliani said morgan stanley cooperated in the governments 
investigation and faces no criminal liability but also indicated 
the firm should have done more to detect wangs activities which 
the former analyst allegedly undertook during much of his 
internship 
morgan stanley spokesman peter roche did not return telephone 
calls for comment on wednesday the firm fired wang after the 
scandal first was disclosed and has stated it believed adequate 
precautions were taken 
lees lawyer james morton at the pittsburgh firm buchanan 
ingersoll pc said in a telephone interview that the criminal 
charges against wang were news to him he declined to comment on 
any aspect of the case or his client 
giuliani said the separate previously undisclosed insider 
trading scheme involving wang included an unidentified person 
living in the chicago area where wang grew up giuliani said the 
person was not a wang relative or engaged in the financial 
business but declined to elaborate 
in that scheme giuliani said wang fed marketsensitive tips 
about developments in at least five companies to the other 
individual who used the information to make profitable trades and 
rewarded wang with about 4000 
wang who attended the university of illinois at 
champaignurbana won a coveted internship at morgan stanley before 
he graduated and was only days short of completing it when the sec 
brought its civil complaint 
</TEXT>
