members of the house banking committee today 
criticized regulators use of promissory notes to rescue insolvent 
savings institutions as a shell game designed to push the 
problem into the next administration 
the federal home loan bank board which regulates the nations 
3000 savings institutions has pledged more than 12 billion over 
the last three weeks to rescue or close 48 savings institutions 
including 21 in texas and 14 in oklahoma states hard hit by the 
depression in the oil industry 
however much of the assistance has been in the form of 
interestbearing notes which will obligate the federal savings and 
loan insurance corp to billions of dollars in payments a year for 
the next decade 
the plan seems to be nothing more than a massive shell game in 
which insolvent institutions are reshuffled the names changed and 
little if any real capital injected resulting in thinly 
capitalized weak institutions said rep charles e schumer 
dny 
many of these institutions will ultimately have to be bailed 
out again at even greater cost to the taxpayer he said 
