<TEXT>
the european economic communitys 
external trade commissioner warned japan thursday to help reduce 
trade imbalances as the eec becomes a more important market for 
japan 
willie de clercq in a speech delivered to a journalists 
conference in berlin and distributed in brussels said the unified 
european market may have to adopt rules to protect some industries 
from excessive imports 
however de clercq brushed aside fears that the eec would become 
more protectionist as it moves to set up a single internal market 
by 1992 as totally unjustified 
the trade commissioner predicted that japans surplus with the 
eec will increase in the second half of 1988 even though it 
slipped during the first half of the year 
de clercq who makes such warnings to japan on a regular basis 
repeated calls for japan to increase imports and to give the eec 
greater access to its markets 
he said the issue was becoming more important as the eec becomes 
a more important trading partner for japan 
the eec is now the big profitable open market for japan 
he said 
he noted that the creation of a single market will create 
unified eec rules on trade and this will benefit foreign companies 
resident in the eec 
he warned at the same time that restrictions at the eec level 
may be set up in certain sensitive sectors to replace various 
national restrictions which currently exist to protect some 
industries 
such community measures would of course be discussed with 
our trading partners and would have to conform fully with our 
international obligations he said 
japans trade surplus with the 12nation trade bloc rose in july 
to 258 billion yen up 14 percent from the yearearlier period 
according to figures distributed thursday by the eec commission 
calculated in dollars the surplus rose in july by 285 percent 
to 19 billion but fell 32 percent in the first seven months of 
1988 compared with the yearearlier period 
the statistics showed japanese imports from the eec rose 162 
percent in yen terms and by 307 percent in dollar terms in the 
month of july nonferrous metals aircraft and textiles showed the 
sharpest growth 
meanwhile japanese exports to the eec rose 151 percent in yen 
terms and 296 percent in dollar terms due primarily to increases 
in exports of automobiles office machinery and audiovisual 
equipment 
