<TEXT>
thousands of chicago commuters were spared a 
morning rushhour nightmare when the chicago amp north western 
railway and one of its unions agreed thurssday to delay a likely 
strike 
both sides agree that this is a step that is in the best 
interest of commuters 41000 of whom use campnw commuter trains 
serving the chicago area said david carle a spokesman for us 
sen paul simon dill 
the 2600 members of the united transportation union at the 
railroad had planned to walk off their jobs at 1201 am cdt 
friday when a 36day coolingoff period ends and the chicago amp 
north western transportation co had planned to lay off 1150 of 
the 2300 union brakemen in its 10state freight operation 
the senate late thursday gave unanimous approval to simons bill 
implementing recommendations of a presidential emergency board 
which in july called for trimming 689 brakemen 
president reagan appointed the panel in april to study the labor 
dispute and seek a solution 
simon predicted the measure would sail through the house on 
friday and win quick approval from reagan he said the bill could 
be passed by late morning and signed an hour or so later by the 
president 
under the railway labor act congress and the president have 
specific authority to settle railroad disputes that threaten 
national commerce 
the railroad and the union have been battling for more than a 
year over the size of train crews on campnw freight trains 
the company contends the brakemens jobs are obsolete and that 
trains can be run with a two or threeman crew an engineer a 
conductor and in some cases a fireman 
the union contends the brakemen two on each trains crew are 
necessary to maintain railroad safety 
the two sides have failed to reach a compromise and earlier this 
week had implemented strike plans 
don markgraf utu general chairman said he opposes federal 
intervention but that the union would honor the settlement if it 
is approved by congress 
the railroad expects congress to push through the legislation 
said campnw spokesman james foote but he noted that management 
personnel had been deployed throughout the freight system and about 
8000 replacement workers had been recalled 
campnw commuters also were bracing for a walkout the third 
threatened this year 
the utu struck campnw for about four hours aug 4 after an 
earlier coolingoff period imposed by president reagan during that 
period the special presidential board proposed a compromise to end 
the impasse 
both sides then rejected the proposal the one now going before 
congress setting the stage for the august strike 
congress however ended that strike quickly by imposing a 
second coolingoff period 
</TEXT>
