champion international corp has reopened 
five pacific northwest mills after workers ratified a threeyear 
contract 
dennis elder a champion spokesman said tuesday the wood 
products company would bring back its 2400 union workers on a 
staggered basis 
the mills had been idle since the workers struck june 6 
elder predicted it would be late this week or early next week 
before all mills were running normally again 
the strike by the western council of industrial workers and 
international woodworkers of america ended last week when workers 
approved a new contract calling for a 1400 signing bonus this 
year a 3 percent wage increase for 1989 and a 4 percent raise in 
1990 
the champion settlement left about 2700 timber workers still on 
strike in the northwest spokesmen for the two unions said 
wednesday 
some 5200 iwa members and 800 western council members are 
voting this week on a proposed settlement with weyerhaeuser co 
results and contract details are to be announced sept 13 
